Non-Linear Dimensionality Reduction Techniques for Single-Cell Transcriptomics¶

Emily Liau from BIOINFORMATICS++

Overview¶

In this tutorial, we will apply two non-linear dimensionality reduction techniques (t-SNE, UMAP) to visualize and annotate major cell types within a single-cell RNA-seq dataset of the small intestinal epithelium from Mus musculus, curated by Haber et al. (2017).

The scRNA-seq analysis workflow encompasses quality control (QC), normalization, feature selection, dimensionality reduction, and clustering (Slovin et al., 2021). Overall, the established thresholds and parameters may have a substantial impact on the results obtained from downstream analyses. The subsequent components of this tutorial provide an overview of various stages of the scRNA-seq workflow, from data pre-processing through dimensionality reduction.

Single-Sample (GSM2836573)¶

First, we will perform data pre-processing and dimensionality reduction on GSM2836573, which requires the following files:

  • GSM2836573_Regional_Duo_M1_barcodes.tsv.gz
  • GSM2836573_Regional_Duo_M1_genes.tsv.gz
  • GSM2836573_Regional_Duo_M1_matrix.mtx.gz

Data Description & Pre-Processing¶

To facilitate data pre-processing for all samples, we will utilize the following packages:

  • scanpy: A module for analyzing scRNA-seq data, including functionality for data pre-processing, visualization, clustering, etc.
  • tarfile: A module that provides read/write functionality for compressed archives

The data for this tutorial are publicly-available, and can be obtained from GSE92332 on NCBI GEO. Within this scRNA-seq experiment, Haber et al. (2017) sought to leverage high-throughput sequencing to extract and process individual cells, in order to establish cell state diversity within the small intestinal epithelium of Mus musculus.

The data for this tutorial are structured as filtered feature-barcode matrices from Cell Ranger by 10x Genomics, with features as rows and barcodes as columns. In a filtered feature-barcode matrix, only cell-associated barcodes are included, and all non-targeted genes are removed during the processing stage.

In this tutorial, we will assess two samples from each of the three primary regions of the small intestine: the duodenum, jejunum, and ileum. Sample ID numbers utilized in this tutorial range from GSM2836573 through GSM2836578, and each sample within the scRNA-seq experiment includes the following file types: barcodes.tsv.gz, genes.tsv.gz, and matrix.mtx.gz.

  • barcodes.tsv.gz: cellular barcodes
  • genes.tsv.gz: ID values of quantified genes
  • matrix.tsv.gz: a matrix of count values, with rows as gene IDs and columns as cellular barcodes

After isolating the required files within your working directory, execute the following code block to output a list of all file names in the folder.

# parse components of file names
string_headers = ['Duo_M1', 'Duo_M2', 'Jej_M1', 'Jej_M2', 'Il_M1', 'Il_M2']
id_values = ['3', '4', '5', '6', '7', '8']
file_base = 'GSM283657'
middle_string = '_Regional_'
mtx_suffix = '_matrix.mtx.gz'
barcode_suffix = '_barcodes.tsv.gz'
gene_suffix = '_genes.tsv.gz'

.matrix.mtx.gz files are read as annotated data matrices, where each data matrix is associated with annotations of observations. Prior to appending samples to the data object, we must initialize the annotated data matrix using the first sample in the directory, Duo_M1.

Each data matrix contains the following features:

  • sample: sample id (Duo_M1, Duo_M2, Jej_M1, Jej_M2, Il_M1, Il_M2)
  • region: region of the small intestine (duodenum, jejunum, ileum)
  • donor: sample donor (M1, M2)
  • n_counts: number of counts
  • log_counts: number of log-transformed counts
  • n_genes: number of genes

In scRNA-seq analysis, QC is often applied on the following covariates: n_counts, log_counts, n_genes. Thus, we perform an initial round of QC during the data loading stage by establishing thresholds to filter out low-quality reads.

In [19]:
# structure file names
header = string_headers.pop(0)
id = id_values.pop(0)
mtx_file = file_dir + file_base + id + middle_string + header + mtx_suffix
barcode_file = file_dir + file_base + id + middle_string + header + barcode_suffix
gene_file = file_dir + file_base + id + middle_string + header + gene_suffix

# load and format matrix data with scanpy
data = sc.read(mtx_file, cache = True)
data = data.transpose()
data.X = data.X.toarray()

# read barcodes and genes from .csv files
barcodes = pd.read_csv(barcode_file, header = None, sep = '\t')
genes = pd.read_csv(gene_file, header = None, sep = '\t')

# annotate data
barcodes.rename(columns = {0:'barcode'}, inplace = True)
barcodes.set_index('barcode', inplace = True)
data.obs = barcodes
data.obs['sample'] = [header] * data.n_obs
data.obs['region'] = [header.split("_")[0]] * data.n_obs
data.obs['donor'] = [header.split("_")[1]] * data.n_obs
genes.rename(columns = {0:'gene_id', 1:'gene_symbol'}, inplace = True)
genes.set_index('gene_symbol', inplace = True)

# filter out low-quality reads via thresholding
data.obs['n_counts'] = data.X.sum(1)
data.obs['log_counts'] = np.log(data.obs['n_counts'])
data.obs['n_genes'] = (data.X > 0).sum(1)

t-SNE¶

The following sections outline examples of applying t-SNE on the Duo_M1 samples with the Louvain and Leiden algorithms.

Louvain (resolution = 1)¶

Prior to applying t-SNE on the Duo_M1 samples, apply the Louvain clustering algorithm (Blondel et al., 2008) with various resolutions on the Duo_M1 samples. The Louvain algorithm serves to identify communities within a graph or network, by assessing the local movement of nodes and constructing an aggregated network (Traag et al., 2019). In the Louvain algorithm, the resolution parameter impacts the size and quantity of the resulting clusters (Lambiotte et al., 2009). The default parameter value is 1; smaller resolutions result in a larger quantity of smaller clusters, and larger resolutions result in a smaller quantity of larger clusters.

PAGA (Louvain, resolution = 0.5)¶

According to Wolf et al. (2019), partition-based graph abstraction (PAGA) generates a topological representation of samples in a dataset, and is commonly applied towards scRNA-seq data to preserve the underlying structure of the samples at various resolutions. PAGA graphs are constructed by associating nodes with partitions, and linking nodes based on the degree of connectivity between partitions. A path in a PAGA graph is the average of all single-cell paths that traverse through a group of cells, allowing individuals to assess the trajectory of the variation in gene expression at the cellular level. The size of the nodes are proportional to the number of cells in the cluster, and the thickness of the edges represent the degree of connectivity.

Construct the PAGA for the t-SNE embedding with the Louvain algorithm at resolution = 0.5.

In [31]:
# construct and plot paga with louvain algorithm (resolution = 0.5)
sc.tl.paga(data, groups = 'louvain_r0.5')
sc.pl.paga_compare(data, basis = 'tsne')

Leiden (resolution = 1)¶

According to Traag et al. (2019), the Leiden algorithm serves to create an aggregate network based on partitions from local node movement. Compared to the Louvain algorithm, the Leiden algorithm is more complex, as it includes a refinement stage when establishing partitions.
Prior to applying t-SNE on the Duo_M1 samples, apply the Leiden clustering algorithm with various resolutions on the Duo_M1 samples.
